                  <note>
                              <ab type="history">Dǝbārwā, located on the right bank of the <placeName ref="LOC4560Marab"/> river, 30km south of 
                        <placeName ref="LOC1579Asmara"/>, was the capital of <title>bāḥǝra nagāš</title>. It was described in the accounts of the European travellers since the sixteenth century.
                        Dǝbārwā was occupied by <persName ref="PRS1500Ahmad"/> in <date>1535</date>, but after his defeat in <date>1543</date>,
                                 resumed its position as <title>bāḥǝra nagāš</title>capital, but fell to the <placeName ref="wd:Q36730"/> who had seized the port of 
                                 <placeName ref="LOC4631Massaw"/> in <date>1557</date>. The commander of <placeName ref="wd:Q36730"/>, 
                                 <persName ref="PRS7692ozdemir"/> established a fort at Dǝbārwā with a long wall and a very high tower. The <placeName ref="wd:Q36730"/>
                                 attempted to use this fort to expand their power into the surrounding areas, but were attacked by the then well-armed local population, and obliged temporarirly to retreat.  
                                 The area was subsequently the site of much fighting in which the <placeName ref="wd:Q36730"/> at times supported by the rebel 
                                 <title>bāḥǝra nagāš</title>
                     <persName ref="PRS10343Yeshaq"/>, fought against two successive emperors <persName ref="PRS7102Minas"/> and 
                                 <persName ref="PRS8550sardaDe"/>. The latter captured the fort and razzed it to the ground in <date>1576</date>. 
                                 Despite this-sided struggle Dǝbārwā maintained
                                 its political and commercial importance for the next two centuries. 
                                 In the mid 18th century the power of <title>bāḥǝra nagāš</title>was usurped by <title>rās</title>
                                 <persName ref="PRS7091Mikael"/> while the town's commercial position was increasingly overshadowed by <placeName ref="LOC1264Adwa"/>. </ab>
                  </note>
